# Conventional Commits

Follow the [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/) specification.

## Format

```
<type>(<scope>): <description>

[optional body]

[optional footer: BREAKING CHANGE or issue refs]
```

## Types

| Type | When to use |
|------|-------------|
| `feat` | New user-facing feature |
| `fix` | Bug fix |
| `refactor` | Internal change with no new feature or bug fix |
| `perf` | Performance improvement |
| `style` | Formatting, whitespace (no logic change) |
| `test` | Adding or fixing tests |
| `docs` | Documentation only |
| `build` | Build system or dependency changes |
| `ci` | CI/CD configuration |
| `chore` | Maintenance tasks (no production impact) |
| `revert` | Reverting a previous commit |

## Rules

- **Imperative mood**: «add», «fix», «remove» — not «added», «fixes», «removed».
- **Subject line ≤ 72 characters**; no trailing period.
- **Scope is optional** but helpful: module, step, or component name (`rescue`, `supplier`, `auth`, `map`…).
- **Body** only when the "why" is not obvious. Separate from subject with a blank line.
- **`BREAKING CHANGE:`** in the footer when the public API changes; also add `!` to the type (`feat!:`).

## Good examples

```text
feat(rescue): move manager field to step 1 for all service types
fix(map): replace PinElement with :pin-options to resolve vnode warning
refactor(supplier): use AdvancedMarker pin-options instead of slot content
perf(supplier-list): debounce search input to reduce API calls
chore(deps): upgrade vue3-google-map to 0.27.1
```

## Bad examples

```text
update files          ❌ too vague
fix bug               ❌ no context
changes               ❌ says nothing
Added new feature.    ❌ past tense and trailing period
FIX: supplier map     ❌ uppercase type, missing scope
```
